://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/GettyImages-1251821969-4x3-1.jpg 1422w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/GettyImages-1251821969-4x3-1.jpg?resize=100,75 100w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/GettyImages-1251821969-4x3-1.jpg?resize=300,225 300w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/GettyImages-1251821969-4x3-1.jpg?resize=768,576 768w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/GettyImages-1251821969-4x3-1.jpg?resize=1024,768 1024w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/GettyImages-1251821969-4x3-1.jpg?resize=683,512 683w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/GettyImages-1251821969-4x3-1.jpg?resize=575,432 575w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/GettyImages-1251821969-4x3-1.jpg?resize=470,352 470w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/GettyImages-1251821969-4x3-1.jpg?resize=600,450 600w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/GettyImages-1251821969-4x3-1.jpg?resize=347,260 347w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/GettyImages-1251821969-4x3-1.jpg?resize=213,160 213w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/GettyImages-1251821969-4x3-1.jpg?resize=207,155 207w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/GettyImages-1251821969-4x3-1.jpg?resize=60,45 60w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/GettyImages-1251821969-4x3-1.jpg?resize=916,687 916w">													</source></source></picture>
					</div>

				
			</span><!-- .has-bugs -->

			
								<figcaption class="caption featured-image-caption">
						South Carolina Sen. Tim Scott dropped a video on April 12 announcing he was forming an exploratory committee for president, a common (though not necessary) first step to declaring candidacy.													<p class="credits">Allison Joyce / Anadolu Agency via Getty Images</p>
											</figcaption>
							
		</figure><!-- .single-featured-image -->

		
			</div>

			
		</div>





<p data-paragraph="main">Earlier this month, Sen. Tim Scott put out a <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pqu52y1B6qc" target="_blank" rel="noopener">slick campaign-style video</a> and announced that he was forming an “exploratory committee” for president. But does that mean he’s actually running?</p>



<p data-paragraph="main">Exploratory committees are essentially a half-measure for the indecisive; they let would-be presidents do many of the things candidates do (raise money, hire a staff, conduct polls) without technically being one. Exploratory committees (also known as <a href="https://www.fec.gov/help-candidates-and-committees/registering-candidate/testing-the-waters-possible-candidacy/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">“testing-the-waters” committees</a>) don’t have to report to the Federal Election Commission, but they do have to follow its rules. And the minute the non-candidate announces their intention to run or takes action to qualify for the ballot, they legally become a candidate and have to report all their financial activity from the exploratory phase.</p>



<p data-paragraph="main">Presidential hopefuls don’t have to form exploratory committees, but many of them do. And almost all of those who do eventually become official candidates. Since the modern primary era began in 1972, at least 89 people<span class="espn-footnote-link" data-footnote-id="1" data-footnote-url="#fn-1" data-footnote-content="&lt;p&gt;Not including Scott.&lt;/p&gt;
"><sup id="ss-1">1</sup></span> have announced an exploratory or testing-the-waters committee for president. Only six ended up not running, the most recent being <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/16/us/politics/16cnd-bayh.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">then-Sen. Evan Bayh</a> in the 2008 election — almost 20 years ago. So it would be a pretty big shock if Scott decides not to take the plunge this year.</p>


<div class="core-html ">
